<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / Economics: US inflation fears may ease
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS in the US that inflation is about to pick up should be allayed this
week if economists' expectations for May producer price inflation prove
correct.
The median forecast is for a rise of 0.2 per cent on the month, following an
unusual 0.6 per cent jump in April.
A sharp 0.4 per cent rise in the so-called core measure of producer price
inflation, which excludes volatile food and energy prices, added to concerns
in April. The core measure for May is forecast to have risen by 0.2 per
cent.
Many analysts believe that the April figures should prove to be an exception
rather than the start of a new trend. In April, price increases for new cars
and tobacco products contributed half of the price rise in the total. Last
month, by contrast, food and energy prices probably declined slightly after
a few months of volatile, but mainly large increases.
Retail sales figures are also out in the US this week. They are expected to
have risen more moderately last month than they did in April. Car sales were
again strong in May following a 3 per cent rise in April.
According to analysts at Midland Global Markets, cars have been the
strongest sales component since the recovery began. Building materials are
also expected to have grown robustly in May.
In the UK, April consumer credit figures are out today. They are expected to
be slightly less robust than in March, reflecting the weakness of retail
sales activity during the month. On Thursday the Central Statistical Office
releases the 1993 edition of Regional Trends, which brings together a wide
range of statistical information on the regions of the UK.
The following are some of the week's other economic highlights. Figures in
brackets are the median of economists' forecasts from MMS International, the
financial information company.
Today: UK, April consumer credit (up Pounds 150m). Spain, May official
reserves (Dollars 44.4bn). Sweden, International Monetary Conference - lasts
until Wednesday. US, April consumer credit (up Dollars 3.3bn). Australia,
May ANZ job ads; April retail trade (up 1 per cent on month); Foundation Day
 -Western Australian markets.
Tomorrow: Sweden, Lloyd Bentsen, US Treasury secretary, addresses
International Monetary Conference. US, April wholesale trade; Johnson
Redbook, week ended June 5. Australia, Q1 housing starts; Council of
Australia government meeting.
Wednesday: US, chairman of National Economic Council addresses Amex
conference in Washington. Sweden, Greenspan and Schlesinger scheduled to
take part in discussion at International Monetary Conference. Japan, Royal
Wedding - all markets closed.
Thursday: Sweden, May consumer prices index (up 0.1 per cent on month, up
5.1 per cent on year). Norway, May CPI (up 0.2 per cent on month, up 2.6 per
cent on year). Germany, holiday in most parts, Frankfurt markets closed. US,
initial claims (339,000), state benefits; 1992 capital spending; money
supply data for week ended May 31; May monthly money supply, M1 (up Dollars
22bn), M2 (up Dollars 27bn), M3 (up Dollars 28bn). Australia, May employment
(up 48,000 on year), May unemployment rate (10.8 per cent).
Friday: France, May CPI (up 0.2 per cent on month, up 2.2 per cent on year),
US, May retail sales (up 0.8 per cent), excluding autos (up 0.5 per cent),
May PPI (up 0.2 per cent on month), excluding food and drink (up 0.2 per
cent on month). Japan, Bank of Japan releases May Tankan Survey.
During the week: Germany, May cost of living, April retail sales (down 1.7
per cent on year). Netherlands, May CPI (up 0.1 per cent on month, up 2.2
per cent on year). Switzerland, Geneva and Zurich CPIs for May, Federal CPI
(up 0.2 per cent on month, up 3.7 per cent on year), May unemployment rate
(5.1 per cent).
</TEXT>
