<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / Two-thirds of workforce show improved skill level
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN HAS experienced a training revolution during the past five years.
Nearly two thirds of workers have increased the level of skill they use in
their jobs, and now as many as 56 per cent of employees use computers or
automated equipment.
That is one of the most important findings of a joint
government/industry-commissioned survey of British employment, published
today by the Policy Studies Institute.
It discovered that 54 per cent of employees received training during the
past three years, compared with only a third who had in 1986. The increase
in skills was particularly sharp among technicians and supervisors.
The survey confounds some of the conventional views of industrial skill
levels in Britain. It found that 65 per cent of employees wanted training,
although only 54 per cent thought they were very or fairly likely to receive
it.
Other key findings in the study, the first of its kind in Britain:
Workers feel their jobs are more stressful than they were five years ago,
with 54 per cent saying stress levels had increased since 1988 and 31 per
cent reporting significant levels of stress as a result of their work.
As many as 67.6 per cent of employees claim they are putting a lot more
effort than formally required into their tasks.
Job insecurity is more widespread than before, particularly among
professional management and skilled manual workers. Men feel more insecure
than women. Frustration and dissatisfaction are considerable among many
workers at the lack of responsibility they feel they are given by their
employers. Just over half the sample believe they should have more say in
decisions relating to changes in the organisation of their work.
The proportion who believe they have a principal say over the amount and
pace of their work has risen from 67 per cent in 1984 to 77 per cent last
year.
Trade unionism has not yet been marginalised in the workplace. While 43 per
cent of employees still belong to unions, 59 per cent said unions were
present in the places in which they worked. Only 9 per cent felt their
employers were trying to discourage union membership.
Most workers feel committed to, rather than alienated from, the enterprises
they work for, but only 29 per cent of them would turn down another job that
offered more pay. Just over a quarter of employees receive incentive pay and
53 per cent have formal appraisals of their work annually.
The survey was conducted between May and September of last year based on a
random sample of 3,855 people in work aged between 20 and 60 with a 72 per
cent overall response rate.
More skilled than we think we are Page 6
Observer Page 13
</TEXT>
