<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / Fingerprint system tenders sought
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HOME OFFICE is within weeks of seeking tenders for the UK's first
comprehensive national automated fingerprint recognition system.
It has chosen Computer Management Group, the privately held computing
services company, to help translate the requirements of the 43 police forces
in England and Wales that will use the system into a technical specification
and to provide quality assurance.
Mr Jonathan Duke-Evans, who is responsible for the project at the Home
Office, said he hoped the specification would be complete by the end of the
summer.
A number of police forces are already making use of an automated fingerprint
recognition service provided by International Business Machines. But the
intention is that the new system, known as Nafis, will for the first time
combine both scene-of-crime matching, which means identifying fingerprints
discovered at the scene of a crime, and personal identification - comparing
a suspect's prints with those held on the database.
Nafis is expected to cost up to Pounds 45m by the time it is ready to go
into service in 1996-97. Mr Duke-Evans said the Home Office had an open mind
on the technology to be employed. It could involve large mainframes or
supercomputers, or a new and advanced technology called neural networking,
based on what scientists know of the working of the human mind.
Nafis is expected to become part of a nationwide criminal identification
system that will include the National Criminal Record System, the
Fingerprint Image System and the Police National Network. The Home Office
has been working with the US Federal Bureau of Investigation to develop
technology for fingerprint recognition.
CMG is one of the largest private computer services companies in Europe,
making pre-tax profits last year of Pounds 9.5m on sales of Pounds 116m.
</TEXT>
