<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The story of the breakfast television company TV-am seems typically British.
Launched by the 'Famous Five' under a policy a bit like that of United
Artists, it ran into trouble when the BBC beat it onto the air with a more
popular programme.
Bickering broke out among TV-am's prima donnas, ratings were appalling, and
the sinking ship had to be saved by the famous rat: Roland. Then, when TV-am
became the most profitable company in the ITV network, the disastrous
Thatcherite auction system was introduced and the most Thatcherite company
of the lot lost its franchise. FT media correspondent Raymond Snoddy tells
the story in Storm In An Egg Cup (7.20 BBC2) a programme originally shown
during the evening called 'TV Hell'. Horizon which follows (8.00) goes for
the biggie: information technology.
Half the US workforce is now employed in the business. Do we need all this
information or is it really a matter of the computer people needing to sell
it? Panorama considers another very modern industry: genetic testing.
</TEXT>
<XX>
