<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / Government widens forestry review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is today seeking the views of interested parties on financial
incentives for planting trees in Britain.
This marks the widening of its review of forestry, which has until now been
conducted behind closed doors.
The Forestry Commission, which owns Britain's public-sector forests, is
launching a rapid consultation exercise, asking for submissions by the end
of July.
It wants those interested to consider whether planting grants should be more
closely targeted, and whether incentives should be redirected to improve the
environmental value of existing forests.
In March Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary and the lead minister responsible
for forestry, said that a committee of officials was reviewing incentives
for forestry in-vestment.
The committee, he said, would also look at options for the ownership of the
Forestry Commission's 900,000 hectares of woodland. Observers believe the
options include privatis-ation.
Environmental groups are likely to urge the planting of woodlands with a
diversity of tree species, and an increase in the provision of facilities
for leisure.
Responses to the consultation should be sent to: Forestry Review Group,
Scottish Office Environment Department, New St Andrew's House, Edinburgh EH1
3TG.
</TEXT>
