<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / Diesel engine reaches Charterhouse Street
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A DIESEL engine weighing nearly 200 tonnes reached its destination in
Charterhouse Street near the edge of the City of London yesterday after
travelling at one mile an hour under police escort from South Mimms,
Hertfordshire. At the junction of Charterhouse Street and Farringdon Road,
the engine's long transporter was driven up on to thick planks so that a
second transporter could be backed under it at right-angles. The second
transporter, designed to avoid any risk of the engine sinking into the car
park underneath Charterhouse Street, carried it to its final destination - a
listed power station nearly 100 years old in which a combined-heat-and-power
facility is being installed. The engine is shown above waiting to be removed
from the first transporter. The facility will be run by Citigen, the power
company owned by British Gas and French-controlled Utilicom. The engine was
the first of two being supplied by Wartsila Diesel of Finland, and the
second will arrive by the same route and method later this month. The two
will be linked to a network of pipes which will provide hot water,
electricity and chilled water for air conditioning to buildings in the City
and surrounding area. The Citigen project is intended to meet the full heat
and power demand of a number of buildings including Guildhall. The system
will have environmental control plant and exhaust-gas equipment aimed at
reducing emissions of sulphur dioxide and oxides of nitrogen by up to 95 per
cent.
</TEXT>
