<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / More skilled, flexible and satisfied than we think we are: A
survey that highlights structural changes in the workplace and dispels a few
misconceptions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONTRARY to popular belief, Britain's workers have adapted to change in a
positive way. They are more skilled and educated in the use of new
technology than ever before. Training provided by employers is more
intensive and longer, and most employees describe it as beneficial.
These are among the findings of the Employment in Britain survey published
today, which provides a graphic portrait of what has been happening in the
country's workplaces over the past five years.
Since 1988 Britain has gone through profound structural change in response
to the twin pressures of technological innovation and global
competitiveness. The survey argues: 'Training has emerged as a major issue
for employees ranking alongside security, pay and supervision.'
Responsive to change, Britain's workers are mostly content with their jobs.
A large majority of the survey sample are 'highly satisfied' not just with
the friendliness of their colleagues but also with the opportunity to use
their abilities. Just over half have a 'high level of satisfaction' with
their supervisors.
However, fewer than half of workers are highly satisfied with their
promotion prospects, the ability and efficiency of their management, their
job security and the number of hours they work.
Assembly-line workers had the lowest level of job satisfaction, followed by
those working with machines and monitoring equipment. Workers who deal
primarily with people scored the most job satisfaction.
Low job satisfaction combines with what the survey describes as a 'sharp
increase in the pressures at work' over the past five years. 'There has been
an intensification of work effort - employees have been required to assume
greater responsibility in their work and quality standards have become more
demanding,' it says.
The survey also reveals a growth in job insecurity since 1988, particularly
among professionals, managers and skilled manual workers. This finding
underlines how Britain's recession has made an impact across a wide range of
occupational groups. Men also feel more insecure in their jobs than women.
At the same time the commitment to work remains fairly strong in Britain.
Just over two thirds of workers would prefer to have a job even if there
were no financial necessity for them to do so.
Nor does there appear to be much antagonism between workers and their
employers. The old 'them' and 'us' divide that used to scar so much of
workplace relations seems virtually to have disappeared. Now as many as two
thirds of workers say they believe their values and those of the
organisations they work for are 'very similar', even if only 9 per cent
'agreed strongly' with that suggestion.
On the other hand, British workers are not committed to working for any
particular company. Less than a third said they would turn down a job with
more pay in order to stay with their current employer. The survey comments:
'It seems clear that British employers have still a great distance to go to
build a work force with a high level of organisational commitment.'
The survey suggests that most British workers do not like to work long hours
 -possibly indicating that the recent European Community directive on
working hours would be more welcome to British workers than it is to the UK
government. The overwhelming preference was for between 16 and 30 hours a
week. Only 2 per cent of men and 0.1 per cent of women would want to work
more than a 40-hour week.
But the pressures on women to work have increased dramatically. In 1980 less
than a quarter of women said they were worried about money but by last year
that figure had risen to 38 per cent.
In 1980 only 37 per cent of women said they worked to pay for necessities
like food, rent or a mortgage; last year that had risen to 53 per cent. 'It
is the increased importance of women's work for meeting housing costs that
explains the greater sense of financial pressure,' the survey says.
The survey finds that worker participation remains relatively low. Fifty-two
per cent of workers are in organisations where they feel that their
influence is low, 30 per cent where worker influence is medium and 18 per
cent where it is high.
Very few British workers have 'a significant say over changes in their
immediate work environment', the survey says. 'As a result a high proportion
of employees are dissatisfied with their existing level of influence.'
It is true, though, that nearly three quarters believe they have a 'great
deal of influence over the amount of work they put in and the quality of
their work', and well over half added they had a 'great deal of influence
over deciding how they were to do their task'.
In recent years workers have gained greater influence over the amount and
pace of the work they do, but the survey found that only a third of workers
in industry felt they had any substantial influence over decisions that
could result in changes in their work.
The survey suggests that workers want to increase their influence more
widely. Nearly half thought they should have more say in decisions affecting
their working lives. Dissatisfaction was pronounced among supervisors and
technicians, skilled manual workers, managers and professionals.
Further findings will be published next year from the survey which the
authors - Mr Duncan Gallie of Nuffield College, Oxford, and Mr Michael White
at the Policy Studies Institute - intend as the first of many.
The overall picture suggests that Britain's employment scene was much more
dynamic and innovative in the late 1980s than many observers believed. It
looks like profound restructuring was taking place in the labour market
among compared with earlier periods.
The trouble is that similar developments may have been going on longer and
more radically among our main competitors. But as the survey points out,
only the US and Sweden have carried out employment surveys comparable to the
British one. Until other European Community countries investigate their
labour markets in similar detail it will remain hard to make credible
international comparisons.
First findings of the survey available from: BEBC Distribution, PO Box 1496,
Poole, Dorset BH12 3YD. Pounds 9.95.
