<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / NHS trusts 'slow' in shifting to local pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL HEALTH Service trusts are only slowly breaking away from nationally
set pay and conditions for their staff, Industrial Relations Services, the
independent employment research company, says today.
Under NHS reforms trusts can employ new staff on locally set pay and
conditions, rather than complying with national agreements. Staff who
transferred to trusts are entitled to retain national terms.
Although three quarters of the 33 trusts surveyed by IRS employ some staff
on local pay and conditions, the proportion of staff in each trust on these
terms is low. Most are senior managers or directors.
Many trusts said a lack of management time and resources was a reason why
moves to devolve setting pay to local managers have been limited. Others
said the government's 1.5 per cent ceiling on public-sector pay had played
its part. Any radical shake-up of pay by trusts was likely to cost far more
than the 1.5 per cent available for this year.
Other findings include:
More trusts have cut staff than increased numbers since gaining
self-governing status. Only two trusts claimed to have derecognised any
unions since opting out. Performance-related pay was restricted to
management in all but two of the trusts that had merit pay.
New recognition agreements with trade unions have been reached by 60 per
cent of trusts in the survey.
IRS Employment Trends. IRS, 18-20 Highbury Place, London N5 1QP. By
subscription.
</TEXT>
