<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / Patten threat to change law on school tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PATTEN yesterday threatened to legislate if necessary to ensure that
next year's national curriculum tests in secondary schools in England and
Wales go ahead.
Speaking as this year's tests - which are expected to be widely disrupted -
are due to start, the education secretary indicated that he would consider
changing the law if this year's experience was unsatisfactory.
Mr Patten said that nothing was ruled in and nothing ruled out to make sure
that next year's tests took place. School governors had a 'statutory duty'
to see that this year's tests were taken, he added.
The tests, which have sparked a long confrontation between the government
and the teachers' unions, are due to start today. The three biggest unions
predict a firm boycott.
This leaves members of the small Professional Association of Teachers alone
in implementing the tests. The PAT's constitution forbids industrial action.
Speaking on BBC 1's Breakfast with Frost, Mr Patten announced that he would
begin a process of publishing the controversial test papers for 14-year-olds
as soon as the exams had been taken.
People would look at the papers and 'wonder what all the fuss was about', Mr
Patten predicted - parents would be 'rather worried' that their children
were not being asked to take them.
Mr Patten said he sympathised with teachers about the level of bureaucracy
that had sprung up in recent years, but argued that the actual papers being
sat were 'very straightforward and very practical'.
He said: 'I don't think we should ever have industrial action in our
classrooms.' It would be a 'tragedy' if - as expected - only 10 per cent of
schools carried out the tests.
Mr Eamonn O'Kane, deputy general secretary of the National Association of
Schoolmasters/Union of Women Teachers, which was the first to announce a
tests boycott, said: 'I would be surprised if more than a handful of schools
end up doing them. I can't imagine that the details will tell Mr Patten
anything other than that this year's tests have been a disaster.'
The National Union of Teachers, the UK's biggest teachers' union, predicted
that parts of the tests might be used for schools' own purposes, 'but
certainly not for the government's purposes'.
The issue of legislation against industrial action first arose earlier this
year when a leaked letter to Mr Patten from Mrs Gillian Shephard, then
employment secretary, suggested that the government was preparing to amend
the Employment Bill to outlaw industrial action which would flout the will
of parliament.
</TEXT>
