<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / 96% of accountants fail to satisfy regulators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUST 4 per cent of the chartered accountants registered to conduct
investment business in England and Wales and visited by regulators last year
were given a completely clean bill of health.
Some 140 - or 11 per cent - of the 1,287 reports on practices visited by
regulators during 1992 highlighted serious breaches, according to figures to
be presented on Wednesday to the council of the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales.
A further 433 firms breached important regulations or a large number of
regulations, and 628 breached minor regulations. Only 55 were judged to have
shown no breaches.
The institute received 63 complaints during the year. Three firms have so
far had their authorisation suspended, while another 49 have been told to
make improvements as a result of reports submitted during the year.
The details come in the annual report from the practice regulation
directorate of the institute, the self-regulating arm which is responsible
for accountants conducting auditing, insolvency and financial services.
Mr Cliff Bygrave, chairman of the institute's Financial Services
Authorisation Committee, said: 'We are never really happy while we have
(significant regulatory breaches). But we have asked (the regulators) to be
stricter and stronger in their visits. Next year is going to be tougher.'
He stressed that many of the breaches were on technical grounds such as
inadequate documentation as a result of 'very heavy regulation' imposed by
the 1988 Financial Services Act.
He said that most did not indicate misappropriation of money or poor
financial advice, but where they did the institute was taking 'the necessary
action'.
At the end of last year, there were 5,556 firms authorised to undertake
investment business, down from 5,851 a year earlier. All but 8 per cent were
registered for 'Category 1' business, which is to provide investment advice.
Just 6 per cent were registered for 'Category 2', allowing them to hold
client money. Only 2 per cent - or 111 firms - were 'Category 3', allowing
discretionary management of funds within certain limits, and a single firm
was registered as 'Category 4', with higher limits on management.
The report from the audit registration committee shows there have been 236
complaints between October 1991 and December 1992. Last year, there were 392
complaints to the insolvency licensing committee.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
