<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / Texas voters rebuff Democrats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MRS Kay Bailey Hutchison, Texas's Republican state treasurer, won a
landslide victory in a by-election on Saturday for one of the state's
national senators. Her election will narrow President Bill Clinton's already
shaky Democratic majority in Congress and perhaps decisively mark the big
south-western state's move away from its Democratic party traditions and
into the Republican camp.
Mrs Hutchison won by a two-to-one margin over the Democrats' Bob Krueger,
who was appointed as interim senator when Mr Lloyd Bentsen left his seat to
join the Clinton administration as Treasury secretary.
Senator Robert Dole, leader of the Republicans in the Senate, said the vote
would send shock waves through Washington and warn members of Congress
against voting for higher taxes.
The Democrats now have a notional 56:44 majority in the Senate, but with
questionable friends such as Senator Richard Shelby of Alabama or Senator
David Boren of Oklahoma Mr Clinton must in fact work with a narrower margin
in seeking to win passage for his legislative agenda.
If other senators do indeed read the vote as a message against taxes, it
could make it harder to push through the Clinton budget package, including
the controversial energy tax which is stalled in the Senate.
Mr Clinton insisted after a strategy meeting with top advisers yesterday
that he would 'stick to the basic principles of the plan,' but he has given
Mr Bentsen some leeway to negotiate modifications with his former colleagues
on the Senate finance committee. The administration remains committed to the
energy tax, but officials say they are willing to reduce its impact by as
much as 30 per cent.
In one respect Mr Krueger's defeat could make it easier for the president to
meet demands for deeper cuts in government spending while demonstrating some
of the toughness that his supporters wish he would show his opponents:
Senator Daniel Moynihan, Mr Bentsen's successor as chairman of the finance
committee, said yesterday that if Texas voters wanted spending cuts rather
than tax increases it would be easy to start on two big Texas projects, the
superconducting supercollider, a costly science project under construction
at Waxahachie, and the space station, for which Nasa is due to present its
new designs this week.
</TEXT>
