<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / Prominent companies admit bribes and kickbacks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAIPEM and Nuovo Pignone, two leading Italian engineering companies, have
admitted to paying more than Dollars 160m (Pounds 104m) in kickbacks and
bribes to win new business in the past six years.
The revelations, contained in their 1992 reports and accounts, indicate the
scale of payments the companies made to obtain big domestic and foreign
contracts and to satisfy Italian political party demands.
The revelations could begin a trend in corporate accounting, as companies
implicated in political corruption reveal to shareholders the scale and
nature of previously secret payments, formerly kept off published balance
sheets and paid via foreign subsidiaries.
Saipem, an engineering group specialising in the energy sector, and Nuovo
Pignone, which makes gas turbines and compressors, are parts of the
state-owned Eni energy and chemicals concern. Eni, whose former chairman, Mr
Gabriele Cagliari, is in prison on corruption allegations, has been deeply
implicated in the scandal.
Saipem's accounts show it paid almost Dollars 121.6m (Pounds 79m) in
kickbacks and 'commissions' to win business between 1987 and 1992, while the
smaller Nuovo Pignone says it paid L25bn (Pounds 11m).
The payments cover both kickbacks to political parties on domestic orders
from public sector companies, such as Enel, and payments to unspecified
foreign intermediaries to win foreign projects.
The accounts of Saipem, whose chairman, Mr Gianni Dell'Orto, was arrested
earlier this year, show Dollars 91.4m was paid between 1987 and 1992 to
companies controlled by Mr Pier Francesco Pacini Battaglia, a Geneva-based
Italian banker who has emerged as a key figure in undeclared payments by the
Eni group. Mr Dell'Orto is today expected to be replaced as chairman at
Saipem's annual meeting.
Almost Dollars 71m of the total is believed to have gone to foreign
intermediaries to help win contracts, while the balance of about Dollars
20.6m was presumably paid to Italian political parties. Saipem says a
further Dollars 50.8m was paid directly by a Zurich subsidiary to unnamed
foreigners. The group says it won about L12,000bn of contracts during the
period.
Although Saipem and Nuovo Pignone are breaking ground in Italian corporate
reporting, the sheer numbers of other leading groups already implicated
suggests it may not be long before others follow.
</TEXT>
