<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 93 / Maxwell pensions shortfall cut to less than Pounds 100m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LESS THAN Pounds 100m in assets stolen from the Maxwell pension funds
remains untraced or in disputed ownership as negotiations intensify for
out-of-court settlements to meet the shortfall.
Investigators have now identified or secured more than three-quarters of the
Pounds 440m they initially believed liquidated or illegally used as
collateral for loans by the late Robert Maxwell, reducing the total
outstanding to far less than originally feared.
The ownership of less than Pounds 100m remains in dispute, but lawyers and
accountants are nearing completion of statements of claim that may lead to
court action over handling the assets or for professional negligence.
The threat of fighting lengthy and costly court actions is intensifying
pressure on City institutions that did business with the Maxwell empire to
contribute instead to the shortfall through the Maxwell Pensioners Trust.
Sir Peter Webster, a retired high court judge and mediation consultant
appointed earlier this year to the trust, has now successfully negotiated a
settlement to a dispute that would otherwise have led to a costly legal
battle.
He hopes to to negotiate settlements in place of up to six potential legal
actions, which would substantially increase the money available to
pensioners.
Goldman Sachs, the US investment bank, is one of several organisations and
individuals that did business with the Maxwell group, and has now paid money
into the fund without admitting any culpability.
Invesco MIM, the fund management group, is coming under increasing pressure
to contribute after its Pounds 750,000 fine and Pounds 1.6m in costs imposed
last week by the Investment Management Regulatory Organisation for breaches
including three relating to Mirror Group pension assets. The Securities and
Investments Board (SIB), the City's senior regulator, is considering using
its powers under Section 61 of the 1988 Financial Services Act to sue
Invesco to seek redress for investors. That would come on top of an existing
Pounds 11.3m action launched by the Mirror Group pension trustees.
SIB could also use its powers for the first time under Section 59 of the act
to ban individuals from the financial services industry and under Section 60
to criticise authorised people.
Most of the Maxwell pension fund assets have been traced. Others - such as
shares in Teva, the Israeli pharmaceutical company, already handed back to
the pension funds - have appreciated in value.
The Maxwell trust fund continues to receive some donations, with the total
to date standing at about Pounds 6.25m. That will allow pensioners to be
paid for a further three years.
Editorial Comment, Page 13
</TEXT>
