<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUN 93 / Air route bids turned down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Transportation Department yesterday dismissed 10 applications by US
airlines to fly new routes between the US and the UK, saying the authorities
sought were not available under the present aviation agreement between the
two countries.
Some route requests stemmed from the requirement that USAir dispose of its
existing US-UK route authorities as part of its tie-up with British Airways.
United Airlines had offered to buy the USAir route authority between
Philadelphia and London if it could move the US end to Chicago and the
London end from Gatwick to Heathrow. Northwest Airlines made a similar offer
for USAir's Baltimore-London authority, seeking to switch the US end to
Detroit.
It had been suggested that, if these proposals were approved by the US and
UK authorities, it could signal a more co-operative approach toward the
liberisation of the skies between the two countries.
Other applications dismissed included Delta's request to fly between New
York and Heathrow, and New York-Manchester.
But the DoT said that it was intent on achieving a 'new, liberal bilateral
understanding with the UK' and that 'this focus on comprehensive reform
necessarily eclipses short-range goals, including the acquisition of rights
to serve a few particular routes'.
</TEXT>
