<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUN 93 / US and Japan move closer on chip trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER and LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO, SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US semiconductor manu-facturers and Japanese electronics companies have
expressed new confidence about improved foreign access to the Japanese
market, in a joint statement that could mark a turning point in the
decade-long battle over semiconductor trade.
'The relationship has turned from confrontation to a new phase, which will
stress mutual prosperity and inter-dependence between foreign semiconductor
suppliers and Japanese users,' said Mr Nobuo Kanoi, executive deputy
president of Sony, following a meeting between US and Japanese industry
executives in Tokyo yesterday.
'We welcome the increased co-operation and understanding that has occurred
under the (1991 US-Japan) Semiconductor Arrangement,' Mr Gil Amelio,
president and chief executive of National Semiconductor, replied on behalf
of the US industry group. 'We also appreciate efforts by both sides which
have led to increased foreign market share.'
The US industry will continue to press for 'gradual and steady improvement
in market access', as stated in the 1991 bilateral trade pact which also
established a target of at least 20 per cent foreign market share by the end
of 1992.
Foreign semiconductor producers achieved a market share of more than 20 per
cent for the first time in the final quarter of last year.
No new market share targets were set at this week's meetings in Tokyo. But
US industry officials noted that the 1991 agreement with its 20 per cent
goal remains in effect until 1996 and that US and Japanese governments will
continue to track market share data.
US industry officials hope to see an average 20 per cent market share over
the next 12 months and are increasingly confident this can be achieved.
The Japanese side remains committed to continued improvement in market
access, but not necessarily market share. US executives insist the two are
synonymous because improved market access is meaningless unless it leads to
higher market share.
However, taking a conciliatory tone, Mr Pat Weber, president of the
components division of Texas Instruments, said that he was confident the US
and Japan would 'move beyond' their disagreements over market share goals.
'We will not rely upon it so heavily in future. We will move forward through
co-operation and trust with our Japanese partners and customers.'
Mr Weber said growing technological dependence between semiconductor makers
and the growing number of cases in which US chips have been designed into
newer products should help to support the US share of the Japanese market.
Mr Hadehiko Yoshida, senior executive vice president of Toshiba concurred:
'We need alliances because semiconductors are becoming so diverse, we need
mutual interdependence to develop them.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3674 Semiconductors and Related Devices.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
