<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUN 93 / Canada's leading lady challenged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON and ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO, MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE RACE for the leadership of Canada's ruling Conservative party has
tightened markedly, raising the possibility that the frontrunner, defence
minister Ms Kim Campbell, may be pipped at the post by Mr Jean Charest, the
youthful environment minister.
About 3,800 Conservative delegates will gather in Ottawa next weekend to
choose a successor to Mr Brian Mulroney both as party leader and prime
minister.
Their main concern will be to pick a leader with the best chance of beating
the opposition Liberals in the general election which must be held before
November.
Up to a few weeks ago, Ms Campbell was seen as virtually invincible in the
leadership race.
But several recent opinion polls indicate that 34-year-old Mr Charest would
fare better in the general election.
A poll published yesterday by Angus Reid Associates concluded that only 29
per cent of decided voters would support a Campbell-led Tory party, with 38
per cent favouring the Liberals. With Mr Charest at the helm, however, the
Tories could expect 34 per cent of the votes, only fractionally behind the
Liberals.
The policy positions of the two candidates are difficult to distinguish. But
Ms Campbell's popularity has been hurt by an unrelenting barrage of media
attention, which has portrayed her as a blunt intellectual out of touch with
the 'real' world.
Despite being a Quebecker, Mr Charest has won admirers throughout the
country with an easygoing style and perfect bilingualism. While organisers
in the Campbell camp remain confident their candidate will win the
leadership, they acknowledge that the vote will be closer than initially
expected.
Moody's Investors Services of New York has reduced its rating on Quebec
government and Hydro-Quebec bonds a notch to A1 from Aa3, or the level
ruling in 1986, writes Robert Gibbens in Montreal.
Quebec finance minister Gerard Levesque said the downgrade was not justified
in view of the government's commitment to wipe out the budget deficit by
1996-97.
</TEXT>
