<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUN 93 / Serb politician charged in Belgrade crackdown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Vuk Draskovic, Serbia's most prominent opposition leader, has been
charged in court with seeking to overthrow the state's constitutional order.
The charge, which could lead to a lengthy prison term, was the latest blow
by the regime of Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic in a crackdown on its
opponents.
Mr Draskovic was arrested earlier this week after leading an anti-government
demonstration in Belgrade and is reported to have been badly beaten. His
lawyers said early today that he had also been charged with assaulting a
police officer. The charges against him carry a penalty of up to 15 years'
jail.
Mr Draskovic was arrested along with his wife and about 20 members of his
Serbian Renewal Movement (SPO). Lawyers said that Mr Draskovic's wife, too,
was charged with attempting to overthrow the state and both would be kept in
custody for at least 30 days.
The Serbian authorities are already seeking a ban on the SPO. The crackdown
on the party follows the ousting of Yugoslav federal president Dobrica Cosic
through a parliamentary vote of no confidence brought by radical Serb
deputies backed by Mr Milosevic's socialists.
In the parliamentary manoeuvring, Mr Milosevic renewed his alliance with
radical nationalists, after their relations had appeared under strain
recently. Mr Vojislav Seselj, head of the Serbian Radical Party, described
the Serbian president as 'a real patriot'.
With the Serbian president asserting his grip on power, the mood in Belgrade
was apprehensive yesterday. New police checkpoints were set up on roads
around the city. For the first time since Mr Milosevic came to power in
1988, the police were an openly intimidating presence. Mr Milosevic is
clearly determined to crack down heavily on any attempt by the opposition to
exploit rising popular discontent over the economic impact of UN sanctions
against Serbia.
Police reinforcements have been brought in from as far as Kosovo in the past
three days, diplomatic sources said. Mr Milosevic has strengthened the
Serbian police force by 20,000 men in the past year, equipping special units
with armoured vehicles and helicopters as well as rocket launchers and other
weaponry.
A year of sanctions has made life in Serbia increasingly uncomfortable,
especially in Belgrade where the effects of large-scale lay-offs, soaring
prices and periodic shortages are most keenly felt.
The opposition has grown weaker since demonstrations last year, led by the
flamboyant Mr Draskovic, demanding an end to the war in Bosnia, forced Mr
Milosevic to call an early election.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>YUZ  Yugoslavia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
    P9229 Public Order and Safety, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
