<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUN 93 / International Company News: Ferruzzi names banks to draw up
restructure plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FERRUZZI, Italy's second-largest industrial grouping, announced yesterday
that it and its parent company, Serafino Ferruzzi, had hired five domestic
banks to draw up a restructuring plan for the financially troubled
agro-industrial, chemicals and energy group.
In a statement, Ferruzzi said the plan called for an industrial and
financial reorganisation of the group and that the five banks - Banca
Commerciale Italiana, Banca di Roma, Credito Italiano, Istituto Bancario San
Paolo di Torino and Mediobanca - would assist it in carrying out the plan.
The statement indirectly confirmed that Mr Sergio Cragnotti, a former
Ferruzzi executive, would not play a role in the restructuring. It had been
widely reported that Mr Cragnotti would assist in the much-needed
recapitalisation of the Ferruzzi group.
The statement also seemed to exclude a role for foreign financial
institutions.
Last week, it had been reported that Goldman Sachs and Citicorp, both of the
US, would advise Ferruzzi in the restructuring.
Although no details have been disclosed, the shake-up, made necessary by the
group's indebtedness, could include a large capital injection supported by
the banks, possibly through an exchange of debts for equity.
Through Serafino, the Ferruzzi family's private holding company, Ferruzzi
has a 45 per cent stake in the stock market-listed Ferruzzi Finanziaria
(Ferfin), which controls Montedison, the food-to-chemicals group.
Ferfin last week reported a loss of L1,519bn (Dollars 1.04bn) in 1992,
compared with a net profit of L115bn in 1991, while Montedison posted a loss
of L1,244bn for 1992, compared with a profit of L168bn in 1991.
The group's consolidated net indebtedness jumped to L15,123bn at the end of
1992 from L8,801bn a year earlier.
Ferruzzi had already announced a disposals plan aimed at concentrating group
assets in the agro-industrial division, while shedding its interests in
chemicals, pharmaceuticals and plastics.
Generali, Italy's largest insurance group, raised consolidated net profit in
1992 by a marginal 0.9 per cent to L675.7bn (Dollars 443m) from L670bn.
</TEXT>
