<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUN 93 / Final moves on Daf buy-out expected soon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A MANAGEMENT buy-out team from the Leyland Daf truck assembly plant at
Leyland, Lancashire, has reached agreement 'on all outstanding commercial
matters' with the administrative receivers to take over the UK operation.
The deal, expected to be finalised next week, is the most important step in
the rescue of the failed Dutch-owned Leyland Daf plant which collapsed into
receivership at the beginning of February.
The buy-out will secure about 700 jobs and opens the way for the rescue of
other parts of the former Leyland Daf business, including the Albion axle
plant in Glasgow, and the Leyland Daf spare parts operation at Chorley,
Lancashire, now trading under the Multipart brand name.
The buy-out team is being backed with Pounds 5m of equity capital by
Barclays Development Capital.
As part of the deal the Leyland site is to be acquired by Lancashire
Enterprises, the development arm of Lancashire County Council. The buy-out
team will purchase the immediate site of the assembly plant.
Mr John Talbot and Mr Murdoch McKillop, joint administrative receivers with
Arthur Andersen, said they were in the process of completing an agreement
with Daf Trucks of the Netherlands to take over the former Leyland Daf sales
and marketing operation based in Thame, Oxfordshire.
Daf Trucks, the new company formed earlier this year to take over the core
medium and heavy duty truck operations of the old Netherlands and Belgian
Daf group, will now market the UK-built Leyland Daf light trucks in the UK
and continental Europe.
</TEXT>
